          <a href="#electrical-standards" class="text-[#1B3A5C] hover:underline py-1">Electrical Standards (NEC / ATEX / IECEx)</a>
          <a href="#electrical-modifications" class="text-[#1B3A5C] hover:underline py-1">Electrical Modifications for Hazardous Area Centrifuges</a>
          <a href="#enclosure-upgrades" class="text-[#1B3A5C] hover:underline py-1">Electrical Enclosures Upgrades</a>
          <a href="#wiring" class="text-[#1B3A5C] hover:underline py-1">Power and Field Sensor Wiring</a>
          <a href="#field-instruments" class="text-[#1B3A5C] hover:underline py-1">Field Instruments, Components, and Gages</a>
          <a href="#mechanical-modifications" class="text-[#1B3A5C] hover:underline py-1">Mechanical Modifications</a>
          <a href="#spark-less-clutches" class="text-[#1B3A5C] hover:underline py-1">Centrifuge Drive Modification — Spark-less Clutches</a>
          <a href="#direct-coupling" class="text-[#1B3A5C] hover:underline py-1">Direct Coupling of Centrifuge Drive</a>
          <a href="#other-upgrades" class="text-[#1B3A5C] hover:underline py-1">Other Upgrades & Safety Devices</a>
          <a href="#summary" class="text-[#1B3A5C] hover:underline py-1">Summary</a>
          <a href="#faq" class="text-[#1B3A5C] hover:underline py-1">Frequently Asked Questions</a>
        </nav>
      </details>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Main Content -->
  <section class="bg-[#F5F5F0]">
    <div class="container mx-auto px-4 max-w-4xl py-12 md:py-16">

      <div class="bg-navy/5 border-l-4 border-gold rounded-r-lg p-4 mb-6">
        <p class="text-sm text-text-light leading-relaxed italic">Dolphin Centrifuge supplies Class 1 Division 2 (C1D2) explosion-proof industrial centrifuge systems for flammable fluid processing in hazardous locations. These certified systems feature explosion-proof motors, compliant control panels, and approved wiring for fuel tank farms, marine engine rooms, and petroleum storage facilities. Models range from 4 to 72 GPM for diesel, lube oil, and waste oil applications. Based in Warren, Michigan, Dolphin Centrifuge has over 40 years of experience in hazardous area centrifuge installations.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- Synopsis -->
      <div id="synopsis" class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-200 shadow-sm p-8 mb-8">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold font-['Plus_Jakarta_Sans'] text-[#1B3A5C] mb-4">Synopsis</h2>
        <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] font-['Source_Sans_3'] text-lg leading-relaxed">
          Industrial centrifuge applications need not be limited by the location or environment being unacceptable for standard machinery. Specially designed centrifuges are safe to install in potentially hazardous environments. In this article, we discuss various considerations and solutions for applying centrifuges in dangerous locations.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- What Is an XP Centrifuge -->
      <div id="explosion-proof-centrifuge" class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-200 shadow-sm p-8 mb-8">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold font-['Plus_Jakarta_Sans'] text-[#1B3A5C] mb-6">Explosion Proof Centrifuge</h2>

        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-8 items-start mb-6">
          <div>
            <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] font-['Source_Sans_3'] leading-relaxed mb-4">
              An explosion-proof centrifuge is a specially designed and manufactured industrial centrifuge for operating in hazardous locations. The possibility of the presence of explosive gases or particles designates specific environments as unsafe. A centrifuge that can safely process under such conditions is classified as explosion-proof.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div>
            <img
              src="/images/explosion-proof-centrifuge/Alfa-Laval-Explosion-Proof-Centrifuge-600-2.jpg"
              alt="Class 1 Div 1 explosion-proof centrifuge for hazardous area installation"
              width="600"
              height="450"
              loading="lazy"
              class="rounded-lg w-full object-cover"
            />
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-500 mt-2 text-center font-['Source_Sans_3']">Class 1 Div 1 — Explosion Proof Centrifuge</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h3 class="text-xl font-bold font-['Plus_Jakarta_Sans'] text-[#1B3A5C] mb-4">Applications</h3>

        <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] font-['Source_Sans_3'] leading-relaxed mb-4">
          Many industrial applications process fluids that have a low flash point and are flammable. In other words, liquids that can easily ignite need specially designed equipment to operate safely. Sub-classifications within this category of hazardous environments depend on the type and presence of such flammable materials.
        </p>

        <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] font-['Source_Sans_3'] leading-relaxed mb-4">
          Authorized governing bodies define specific details on area classifications. UL documentation provides detailed hazardous area classification criteria for North American installations.
        </p>

        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 items-start">
          <div>
            <img
              src="/images/explosion-proof-centrifuge/alfa-laval-class1-div2-hazardous-area-centrifuge-offshore-400.jpg"
              alt="Class 1 Div 2 diesel centrifuge installed on offshore oil and gas platform"
              width="400"
              height="300"
              loading="lazy"
              class="rounded-lg w-full object-cover"
            />
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-500 mt-2 text-center font-['Source_Sans_3']">Class 1 Div 2 Diesel Centrifuge — Offshore Platform</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-blue-50 border-l-4 border-[#1B3A5C] p-4 rounded-r-lg">
            <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] font-['Source_Sans_3'] text-sm leading-relaxed">
              Authorized governing bodies define specific details on area classifications. The UL (Underwriters Laboratories) system provides detailed hazardous area classification criteria used across North American installations. Different regional standards (NEC, ATEX, IECEx) apply depending on where the centrifuge is installed.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Applications Section -->
      <div id="applications" class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-200 shadow-sm p-8 mb-8">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold font-['Plus_Jakarta_Sans'] text-[#1B3A5C] mb-6">Applications Requiring Area Classified Centrifuges</h2>

        <!-- Class 1 Div 1 -->
        <div id="class1-div1" class="mb-8">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-bold font-['Plus_Jakarta_Sans'] text-[#1B3A5C] mb-4">Class 1 Division 1 Centrifuge Applications</h3>

          <div class="bg-red-50 border border-red-200 rounded-lg p-4 mb-6">
            <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] font-['Source_Sans_3'] leading-relaxed">
              <strong>Class 1 Division 1</strong> areas are classified as locations where explosion or fire hazards exist due to the presence of flammable gases, flammable or combustible liquid-produced vapors, combustible dust, or ignitable fibers or flyings.
            </p>
          </div>

          <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] font-['Source_Sans_3'] leading-relaxed mb-6">
            The following are typical examples of such explosion-proof centrifuge applications. We briefly describe the considerations for centrifuge execution for petroleum refineries.
          </p>

          <!-- Petroleum Refineries -->
          <div id="petroleum-refineries" class="bg-gray-50 rounded-lg p-6 mb-6">
            <h4 class="text-lg font-bold font-['Plus_Jakarta_Sans'] text-[#1B3A5C] mb-4">Centrifuge for Petroleum Refineries</h4>
            <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 items-start">
              <div>
                <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] font-['Source_Sans_3'] leading-relaxed mb-3">
                  Crude oil refineries process crude oil feedstock to produce final products such as solvents, condensate, gasoline, diesel, naphtha, kerosene, etc. All of these petroleum components are flammable and therefore require safe processing by using explosion-proof centrifuges.
                </p>
                <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] font-['Source_Sans_3'] leading-relaxed mb-3">
                  The hazardous area classification of the centrifuge depends on the actual location of the centrifuge. If the centrifuge is in an area in the presence of flammable liquids, vapors, or gases, it needs to be suitable for the Class 1 Div 1 environment.
                </p>
                <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] font-['Source_Sans_3'] leading-relaxed mb-3">
                  The photograph shown here illustrates a centrifuge suitable for NEC Class 1 Division 1 Groups C & D hazardous area installation. This type of centrifuge is commonly deployed in petroleum refinery environments where flammable vapors and gases may be present continuously during normal operations.
                </p>
                <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] font-['Source_Sans_3'] leading-relaxed">
                  On the other hand, if the centrifuge application is in a relatively safer area where such flammable material is not usually present, a Class I Div 2 certified centrifuge may be adequate, like the one shown below.
                </p>
              </div>
              <div>
                <img
                  src="/images/explosion-proof-centrifuge/Alfa-Laval-Diesel-Centrifuge-Class-1-Div-2-Explosion-Proof-600-1.jpg"
                  alt="Diesel centrifuge Class 1 Div 2 explosion-proof for petroleum refinery application"
                  width="600"
                  height="450"
                  loading="lazy"
                  class="rounded-lg w-full object-cover"
                />
                <p class="text-xs text-gray-500 mt-2 text-center font-['Source_Sans_3']">Diesel Centrifuge — Class 1 Div 2 Explosion Proof</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Offshore Gas Platform -->
          <div class="mb-4">
            <h4 class="text-lg font-bold font-['Plus_Jakarta_Sans'] text-[#1B3A5C] mb-3">Class 1 Div 1 Explosion Proof Centrifuge — Offshore Gas Platform</h4>
            <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] font-['Source_Sans_3'] leading-relaxed mb-4">
              Similarly, an Offshore Oil and Gas Platform centrifuge system could require a specific hazardous area classification based on the final installation location. Offshore platforms present unique challenges because flammable gases and vapors may be present in varying concentrations depending on the specific area of the platform. The centrifuge and all associated control equipment must be certified for the appropriate Class and Division based on a thorough assessment of the installation location.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Class 1 Div 2 -->
        <div id="class1-div2" class="mb-8">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-bold font-['Plus_Jakarta_Sans'] text-[#1B3A5C] mb-4">Class 1 Division 2 (C1D2) Hazardous Area Centrifuge Applications</h3>

          <div class="bg-yellow-50 border border-yellow-200 rounded-lg p-4 mb-6">
            <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] font-['Source_Sans_3'] leading-relaxed">
              <strong>Class 1 Division 2</strong> areas are classified as locations where volatile flammable liquids or flammable gases or vapors exist but are generally confined within closed containers.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-4 mb-6">
            <div class="col-span-1">
              <img
                src="/images/explosion-proof-centrifuge/DMPX-028-Class-1-Div-2-Duplex-Diesel-Centrifuge-Module-600.jpg"
                alt="DMPX-028 Class 1 Div 2 duplex diesel centrifuge module"
                width="600"
                height="450"
                loading="lazy"
                class="rounded-lg w-full object-cover"
              />
              <p class="text-xs text-gray-500 mt-2 text-center font-['Source_Sans_3']">DMPX-028 Class 1 Div 2 Duplex Diesel Centrifuge Module</p>
            </div>
            <div class="col-span-1">
              <img
                src="/images/explosion-proof-centrifuge/Alfa-Laval-3-Phase-Centrifuge-Class-1-Div-2-Crude-Oil-Hawaii-300.jpg"
                alt="3-phase centrifuge Class 1 Div 2 for crude oil processing"
                width="300"
                height="300"
                loading="lazy"
                class="rounded-lg w-full object-cover"
              />
              <p class="text-xs text-gray-500 mt-2 text-center font-['Source_Sans_3']">Centrifuge Class 1 Div 2 — Crude Oil</p>
            </div>
            <div class="col-span-1">
              <img
                src="/images/explosion-proof-centrifuge/SS-Food-Grade-Decanter-C1D2-Alcohol-Processing-600-1.jpg"
                alt="Stainless steel food-grade decanter centrifuge Class 1 Div 2 for alcohol slurry processing"
                width="600"
                height="450"
                loading="lazy"
                class="rounded-lg w-full object-cover"
              />
              <p class="text-xs text-gray-500 mt-2 text-center font-['Source_Sans_3']">Stainless Steel (Food Grade) Decanter Centrifuge for Hazardous Areas Class 1 Div 2 for Alcohol Slurry Processing</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] font-['Source_Sans_3'] leading-relaxed mb-6">
            The following example illustrates the explosion-proof equipment considerations for industries that use flammable solvents such as ethanol for extraction processes.
          </p>

          <!-- Hemp Ethanol Extraction -->
          <div id="hemp-ethanol-extraction" class="bg-gray-50 rounded-lg p-6">
            <h4 class="text-lg font-bold font-['Plus_Jakarta_Sans'] text-[#1B3A5C] mb-3">Hemp Ethanol Extraction Centrifuge</h4>
            <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 items-start">
              <div>
                <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] font-['Source_Sans_3'] leading-relaxed mb-3">
                  Alcohol is the solvent of choice for CBD oil extraction from hemp plants. Ethanol alcohol has a low flash point and is considered a hazardous fluid. Therefore, decanter centrifuges used for hemp biomass separation from ethanol must meet hazardous area certification.
                </p>
                <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] font-['Source_Sans_3'] leading-relaxed mb-3">
                  The image shown here is that of a large-volume <strong>Class 1 Div 2 Explosion Proof Centrifuge</strong> rated at 40 GPM for ethanol-based hemp extraction processes.
                </p>
                <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] font-['Source_Sans_3'] leading-relaxed mb-3">
                  Since the hemp solvent extraction is a closed (isolated from the environment) system, Class 1 Div 2 certified components are adequate for such locations. Suppose the hemp producer uses a hydrocarbon-based solvent as the extraction medium. In that case, careful consideration and professional consultation are recommended to identify and implement the right hazardous area classification.
                </p>
                <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] font-['Source_Sans_3'] leading-relaxed">
                  Another very similar application is for THC extraction from cannabis using solvents or ethanol. These solvent-based extraction processes all share the same fundamental requirement for hazardous area classification due to the flammable nature of the extraction solvents.
                </p>
              </div>
              <div>
                <img
                  src="/images/explosion-proof-centrifuge/hemp-centrifuge-explosion-proof-300x300.jpg"
                  alt="Large volume hemp centrifuge explosion-proof Class 1 Div 2 rated at 40 GPM"
                  width="300"
                  height="300"
                  loading="lazy"
                  class="rounded-lg w-full object-cover"
                />
                <p class="text-xs text-gray-500 mt-2 text-center font-['Source_Sans_3']">Large Volume Hemp Centrifuge — Explosion Proof — 40 GPM</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Stainless Steel Disc Stack XP -->
          <div class="mt-6">
            <img
              src="/images/explosion-proof-centrifuge/Alfa-Laval-Disc-Stack-Centrifuge-Stainless-Steel-Explosion-Proof.jpg"
              alt="Stainless steel disc stack centrifuge in explosion-proof configuration"
              width="600"
              height="400"
              loading="lazy"
              class="rounded-lg w-full max-w-lg mx-auto block"
            />
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-500 mt-2 text-center font-['Source_Sans_3']">Disc Stack Centrifuge — Stainless Steel Explosion Proof</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Purged Centrifuges -->
        <div id="purged-centrifuges">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-bold font-['Plus_Jakarta_Sans'] text-[#1B3A5C] mb-4">Uses for Purged Centrifuges</h3>

          <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 items-start mb-4">
            <div>
              <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] font-['Source_Sans_3'] leading-relaxed mb-4">
                In specific applications, the centrifuges may be purged with an inert gas to blanket the internals. This constant purging prevents the buildup of vapors from the process fluid. This purging is an added safety measure. This methodology also helps in cases where the gases or odors are a potential health hazard for the local operators.
              </p>
              <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] font-['Source_Sans_3'] leading-relaxed mb-4">
                An inert gas purging system coupled with a low vacuum venting system helps prevent the operating area from being free of such gases and odors.
              </p>
              <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] font-['Source_Sans_3'] leading-relaxed mb-4">
                For example, centrifuges operating on <a href="/crude-oil-tank-bottom-recovery-centrifuge/" class="text-[#1B3A5C] hover:underline font-semibold">crude oil tank bottoms</a> could potentially be inert gas purged and vented to alleviate the presence of hydrogen sulfide gas in the operating area.
              </p>
              <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] font-['Source_Sans_3'] leading-relaxed">
                Inert gas blanketing isolates the process fluid from the atmosphere to prevent oxidation and related chemical deterioration. <a href="/beer-wine-centrifuge/" class="text-[#1B3A5C] hover:underline font-semibold">Centrifuges used to process wine and beer</a> must keep the process fluid away from the air to prevent oxidation. This application is an example of purging for a non-hazardous centrifuge application.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div>
              <img
                src="/images/explosion-proof-centrifuge/Alfa-Laval-MAB-206-Disc-Stack-Centrifuge-Explosion-Proof-Class-1-Div-2.jpg"
                alt="Disc stack centrifuge explosion-proof Class 1 Div 2 configuration"
                width="600"
                height="450"
                loading="lazy"
                class="rounded-lg w-full object-cover"
              />
              <p class="text-xs text-gray-500 mt-2 text-center font-['Source_Sans_3']">Disc Stack Centrifuge — Explosion Proof Class 1 Div 2</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Electrical Standards -->
      <div id="electrical-standards" class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-200 shadow-sm p-8 mb-8">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold font-['Plus_Jakarta_Sans'] text-[#1B3A5C] mb-4">Electrical Standards for Explosion-Proof & Hazardous Areas</h2>

        <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] font-['Source_Sans_3'] leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Depending on the region, different types of hazardous area classifications apply to specific area locations. We have broadly summarized the three primary systems of classification in use worldwide. Again, specific details on each guideline are on the included links under each heading.
        </p>

        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-6">

          <!-- N. America -->
          <div class="bg-gray-50 rounded-lg p-5 border border-gray-200">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-bold font-['Plus_Jakarta_Sans'] text-[#1B3A5C] mb-3">N. America (NEC / CEC)</h3>
            <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] font-['Source_Sans_3'] text-sm leading-relaxed mb-3">
              Permissible components for use in hazardous areas in N. America must comply with requirements issued by <strong>NEC (National Electrical Code)</strong> and <strong>CEC (Canadian Electrical Code)</strong> standards.
            </p>
            <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] font-['Source_Sans_3'] text-sm leading-relaxed mb-3">
              The UL system designates Classes and Divisions within each Class. In comparison, the new Canadian system sets zones within each Class. There are significant differences between the division and zone classifications.
            </p>
            <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] font-['Source_Sans_3'] text-sm leading-relaxed">
              UL (Underwriters Laboratories) provides certification and marking for equipment intended for use in classified hazardous locations. A typical UL marking tag identifies the specific Class, Division, and Group designations that the equipment is rated for.
            </p>
            <div class="mt-3 bg-blue-50 rounded p-2 text-xs font-['JetBrains_Mono'] text-[#1B3A5C]">
              Class 1 Div 1 / Div 2<br/>
              Groups A, B, C, D
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- European Union -->
          <div class="bg-gray-50 rounded-lg p-5 border border-gray-200">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-bold font-['Plus_Jakarta_Sans'] text-[#1B3A5C] mb-3">European Union (ATEX)</h3>
            <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] font-['Source_Sans_3'] text-sm leading-relaxed mb-3">
              The European electrical and protective equipment certification system in Europe is commonly known as the <strong>ATEX directive</strong>. Per the official document, "Equipment and protective systems intended for use in potentially explosive atmospheres (ATEX) cover a range of products, including those used on fixed offshore platforms, petrochemical plants, mines, and flour mills, amongst others."
            </p>
            <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] font-['Source_Sans_3'] text-sm leading-relaxed">
              A typical example of a centrifuge suitable for hazardous locations would be marked as <strong>ATEX II 3 G (Zone 2) II B T3.</strong> The reader can reference specific zone details in the official ATEX summary documentation. ATEX marking tags identify the zone classification, gas group, and temperature class.
            </p>
            <div class="mt-3 bg-blue-50 rounded p-2 text-xs font-['JetBrains_Mono'] text-[#1B3A5C]">
              Zone 1 / Zone 2<br/>
              ATEX II 3G, IIB T3
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- International -->
          <div class="bg-gray-50 rounded-lg p-5 border border-gray-200">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-bold font-['Plus_Jakarta_Sans'] text-[#1B3A5C] mb-3">International (IECEx)</h3>
            <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] font-['Source_Sans_3'] text-sm leading-relaxed mb-3">
              IS (International Standard) has guidelines for hazardous area designation and compliance, similar to the ATEX guidelines. The <strong>IEC (International Electrotechnical Commission)</strong> maintains these standards.
            </p>
            <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] font-['Source_Sans_3'] text-sm leading-relaxed">
              IECEx certification is recognized in many countries outside North America and the EU, providing a globally consistent framework for hazardous area electrical equipment certification and compliance.
            </p>
            <div class="mt-3 bg-blue-50 rounded p-2 text-xs font-['JetBrains_Mono'] text-[#1B3A5C]">
              IECEx Zone 1 / Zone 2<br/>
              IEC 60079 Series
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- ATEX image -->
        <div class="mt-6">
          <img
            src="/images/explosion-proof-centrifuge/DMPX-014-Duplex-Disc-Stack-Centrifuge-Skid-for-HFO-and-Diesel-ATEX-Zone-2-600.jpg"
