          />
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-500 mt-2 text-center font-['Source_Sans_3']">DMPX-014 Duplex Disc Stack Centrifuge Skid for HFO and Diesel — ATEX Zone 2</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Considerations for Explosion-Proof Centrifuge Adaptation -->
      <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-200 shadow-sm p-8 mb-8">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold font-['Plus_Jakarta_Sans'] text-[#1B3A5C] mb-6">Considerations for Explosion-Proof Centrifuge Adaptation</h2>
        <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] font-['Source_Sans_3'] leading-relaxed mb-4">
          Converting a standard industrial centrifuge for use in a hazardous area requires a comprehensive set of modifications spanning both the electrical and mechanical systems. The following sections detail the specific categories of modifications required to achieve hazardous area compliance for industrial centrifuge installations.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Electrical Modifications -->
      <div id="electrical-modifications" class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-200 shadow-sm p-8 mb-8">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold font-['Plus_Jakarta_Sans'] text-[#1B3A5C] mb-4">Electrical Modifications for Hazardous Area Centrifuges</h2>

        <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] font-['Source_Sans_3'] leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Electrical components used on industrial centrifuges designed for hazardous areas must meet the designated classification and be certified to the same standard. These parts fall into the following categories.
        </p>

        <!-- Electrical Enclosures -->
        <div id="enclosure-upgrades" class="mb-8">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-bold font-['Plus_Jakarta_Sans'] text-[#1B3A5C] mb-4">Electrical Enclosures Upgrades</h3>
          <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 items-start">
            <div>
              <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] font-['Source_Sans_3'] leading-relaxed mb-4">
                Industrial electrical enclosures house various electrical components, which can cause sparking during routine operations. These sparks can cause flammable gases or vapors to ignite if they are present in high concentrations. Therefore centrifuge control system enclosures need to be appropriately isolated from the surrounding environment through proper sealing.
              </p>
              <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] font-['Source_Sans_3'] leading-relaxed mb-4">
                Depending on the classification level, an inert gas purging system may be installed on the enclosure, as shown in the adjacent photograph. This device creates and maintains an inert gas atmosphere within the enclosure that prevents the ignition of flammable gases or vapors by replacing oxygen.
              </p>
              <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] font-['Source_Sans_3'] leading-relaxed">
                The next level of enclosure classification to Class I Div 1 specification involves cast metal housing designed to contain thermal events within the enclosures. Specially rated electrical fittings and joint seals isolate these containment enclosures from the surrounding environment.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div>
              <img
                src="/images/explosion-proof-centrifuge/Class-1-Div-2-Nitrogen-Purge-Centrifuge-System-300.jpg"
                alt="Nitrogen purge device for Class 1 Div 2 centrifuge control enclosure"
                width="300"
                height="300"
                loading="lazy"
                class="rounded-lg w-full max-w-xs"
              />
              <p class="text-xs text-gray-500 mt-2 font-['Source_Sans_3']">Nitrogen Purge Device</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Wiring -->
        <div id="wiring" class="mb-8">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-bold font-['Plus_Jakarta_Sans'] text-[#1B3A5C] mb-4">Power and Field Sensor Wiring for Classified Centrifuge Systems</h3>
          <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] font-['Source_Sans_3'] leading-relaxed mb-4">
            Field sensor wiring refers to small gauge wires used to connect the pressure, vibration, temperature, and other sensors to the control system. Typically these are low-voltage conductors, but they still need to be routed through a rigid conduit with specialized fittings and glands. These fittings are sealed at the instrument and control panel to prevent the ingress of gases or vapors into the device or control enclosure.
          </p>
          <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] font-['Source_Sans_3'] leading-relaxed">
            Similar guidelines apply to power wiring that supplies power to components such as centrifuge drive motors and process fluid heaters. Power wiring also requires routing through approved conduits and truncated with certified and sealed glands.
          </p>
        </div>

        <!-- Field Instruments -->
        <div id="field-instruments">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-bold font-['Plus_Jakarta_Sans'] text-[#1B3A5C] mb-4">Field Instruments, Components, and Gages for XP Centrifuges</h3>
          <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 items-start">
            <div>
              <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] font-['Source_Sans_3'] leading-relaxed mb-4">
                Field instruments or sensors are required for the reliable operation of centrifuges. These sensors include temperature, pressure, level, and flow sensors, which must be certified by the relevant authority to meet the applicable classification requirements.
              </p>
              <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] font-['Source_Sans_3'] leading-relaxed">
                Another component widely used on centrifuges is solenoid valves. Specific solenoid valves are certified for hazardous area applications and allowable for use in such applications.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div>
              <img
                src="/images/explosion-proof-centrifuge/Explosion-Proof-Sensors-ADDAX-Diesel-Centrifuge.jpg"
                alt="Explosion-proof sensors installed on ADDAX diesel centrifuge system"
                width="600"
                height="400"
                loading="lazy"
                class="rounded-lg w-full object-cover"
              />
              <p class="text-xs text-gray-500 mt-2 text-center font-['Source_Sans_3']">Explosion Proof Sensors — ADDAX Diesel Centrifuge</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Mechanical Modifications -->
      <div id="mechanical-modifications" class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-200 shadow-sm p-8 mb-8">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold font-['Plus_Jakarta_Sans'] text-[#1B3A5C] mb-6">Mechanical Modifications for Explosion-Proof Centrifuges</h2>

        <!-- Spark-less Clutches -->
        <div id="spark-less-clutches" class="mb-8">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-bold font-['Plus_Jakarta_Sans'] text-[#1B3A5C] mb-4">Centrifuge Drive Modification — Spark-less Clutches</h3>
          <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] font-['Source_Sans_3'] leading-relaxed mb-4">
            Industrial centrifuges have friction clutches as part of the main power transmission, which uses a rotating friction element mounted on a steel shoe. This assembly contacts the centrifuge drum and transmits the torque through friction.
          </p>
          <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] font-['Source_Sans_3'] leading-relaxed">
            In case of excessive wear of the friction elements, the steel components contacting each other at high speed can cause sparking. Therefore, these steel shoes are sometimes replaced with brass or other non-ferrous metal. Friction between steel and brass components prevents sparks from being generated.
          </p>
        </div>

        <!-- Direct Coupling -->
        <div id="direct-coupling" class="mb-8">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-bold font-['Plus_Jakarta_Sans'] text-[#1B3A5C] mb-4">Direct Coupling of Centrifuge Drive</h3>
          <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] font-['Source_Sans_3'] leading-relaxed mb-4">
            Direct coupling of the drive components is the preferred way to avoid the clutch sparking issue. In this modification, a coupling disc bolted to the horizontal shaft drum replaces the rotating clutch assembly.
          </p>
          <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] font-['Source_Sans_3'] leading-relaxed">
            However, this adaptation also means that the drive motor has to overcome the entire rotating mechanism's inertia, including the heavy bowl assembly. Therefore, a power inverter in the control system is a part of the adaptation. An inverter allows the motor to ramp up to operating speed over a defined time window without drawing excessive current.
          </p>
        </div>

        <!-- Comparison table -->
        <div class="overflow-x-auto">
          <table class="w-full text-sm font-['Source_Sans_3'] border-collapse">
            <thead>
              <tr class="bg-[#1B3A5C] text-white">
                <th class="text-left p-3">Drive Type</th>
