      <!-- FAQ Section -->
      <div id="faq" class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-200 shadow-sm p-8 mb-8">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold font-['Plus_Jakarta_Sans'] text-[#1B3A5C] mb-6">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

        <div class="space-y-4">
          <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4 group">
            <summary class="cursor-pointer font-semibold text-[#1B3A5C] font-['Plus_Jakarta_Sans'] flex items-center justify-between">
              <span>What is an explosion-proof centrifuge?</span>
              <span class="group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform text-[#E8A317]">▼</span>
            </summary>
            <div class="mt-3 text-[#2D2D2D] font-['Source_Sans_3'] leading-relaxed">
              <p>An explosion-proof centrifuge is a specially designed and manufactured industrial centrifuge for operating in hazardous locations. The possibility of the presence of explosive gases or particles designates specific environments as unsafe. A centrifuge that can safely process under such conditions is classified as explosion-proof. These centrifuges feature certified electrical enclosures, spark-free drive mechanisms, and specialized sensors and wiring to prevent ignition of flammable materials.</p>
            </div>
          </details>

          <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4 group">
            <summary class="cursor-pointer font-semibold text-[#1B3A5C] font-['Plus_Jakarta_Sans'] flex items-center justify-between">
              <span>What is the difference between Class 1 Div 1 and Class 1 Div 2 centrifuges?</span>
              <span class="group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform text-[#E8A317]">▼</span>
            </summary>
            <div class="mt-3 text-[#2D2D2D] font-['Source_Sans_3'] leading-relaxed">
              <p class="mb-2">Class 1 Division 1 areas are locations where explosion or fire hazards exist due to the continuous presence of flammable gases, combustible liquid-produced vapors, combustible dust, or ignitable fibers. Class 1 Division 2 areas are locations where volatile flammable liquids or flammable gases exist but are generally confined within closed containers.</p>
              <p>Class 1 Div 1 centrifuges require more stringent modifications including cast metal housings designed to contain thermal events and fully sealed enclosures, while Class 1 Div 2 centrifuges may use nitrogen-purged enclosures to maintain an inert atmosphere.</p>
            </div>
          </details>

          <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4 group">
            <summary class="cursor-pointer font-semibold text-[#1B3A5C] font-['Plus_Jakarta_Sans'] flex items-center justify-between">
              <span>What electrical modifications are needed for a hazardous area centrifuge?</span>
              <span class="group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform text-[#E8A317]">▼</span>
            </summary>
            <div class="mt-3 text-[#2D2D2D] font-['Source_Sans_3'] leading-relaxed">
              <p>Hazardous area centrifuges require several electrical modifications: upgraded enclosures with inert gas purging or cast metal containment housings, rigid conduit routing with specialized fittings and sealed glands for both sensor and power wiring, and certified field instruments including temperature, pressure, level, and flow sensors rated for the applicable classification. Solenoid valves must also be certified for hazardous area use. All wiring, whether for low-voltage field sensors or high-power drive motors, must be routed through approved conduits and terminated with certified sealed glands.</p>
            </div>
          </details>

          <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4 group">
            <summary class="cursor-pointer font-semibold text-[#1B3A5C] font-['Plus_Jakarta_Sans'] flex items-center justify-between">
              <span>How are centrifuge drives modified for explosion-proof applications?</span>
              <span class="group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform text-[#E8A317]">▼</span>
            </summary>
            <div class="mt-3 text-[#2D2D2D] font-['Source_Sans_3'] leading-relaxed">
              <p class="mb-2">Two primary mechanical modifications address spark risk in centrifuge drives. First, standard steel friction clutch shoes can be replaced with brass or other non-ferrous metals to prevent sparking during contact at high speed.</p>
              <p>Second, and preferred, the friction clutch can be eliminated entirely through direct coupling using a coupling disc bolted to the horizontal shaft drum. Direct coupling requires a power inverter (VFD) in the control system to allow the motor to ramp up to operating speed over a defined time window without drawing excessive current, since the motor must overcome the entire rotating mechanism's inertia including the heavy bowl assembly.</p>
            </div>
          </details>

          <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4 group">
            <summary class="cursor-pointer font-semibold text-[#1B3A5C] font-['Plus_Jakarta_Sans'] flex items-center justify-between">
              <span>What hazardous area certifications are available for industrial centrifuges?</span>
              <span class="group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform text-[#E8A317]">▼</span>
            </summary>
            <div class="mt-3 text-[#2D2D2D] font-['Source_Sans_3'] leading-relaxed">
              <p>Industrial centrifuges can be certified under three primary classification systems: NEC/CEC (North America) with Class and Division designations using the UL certification system, ATEX (European Union) with Zone designations for explosive atmospheres covering equipment used on offshore platforms, petrochemical plants, and more, and IECEx (International) maintained by the International Electrotechnical Commission for global installations. Dolphin Centrifuge provides centrifuge systems certified to all three standards depending on the installation region and specific requirements.</p>
